04968nam a22007335i 9781846155727DE-B159720240306014423.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20072007xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a97818461557277 a10.1515/97818461557272doi  a(DE-B1597)674839  a(OCoLC)1097122399  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcUK 7aHIS0370102bisacsh04a809.93352qOCoLC222/eng/20230216  aEC 5128qBSZ2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/20594:120231 aCowell, Andrew, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Medieval Warrior Aristocracy :bGifts, Violence, Performance, and the Sacred /cAndrew Cowell.31aWoodbridge, Suffolk : bBoydell and Brewer, c[2007] 1bD.S.Brewer, c[2007] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (206 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aGallica ;v600tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgements -- tIntroduction -- t1 The Power of Giving -- t2 The Symbolic Constitution of the Giving Subject: William the Conqueror and Robert Guiscard -- t3 Violence and “Taking”: Towards a Generalized Symbolic Economy -- t4 Taking an Identity: The Poem of the Cid -- t5 The Sacred Kept -- t6 The Hero, Gratuity and Alterity: The Song of Roland -- t7 The Supplemental Hero: Raoul of Cambrai -- t8 Female Integrity and Masculine Desires in The Nibelungenlied -- t9 Fractured Identities, and the Solution of Chivalry: William of Orange -- tConclusion: A New, Different Warrior Aristocracy -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA major reconsideration of the relationship between warrior aristocrats, epics, and heroes in medieval culture.The process of identity formation during the central Middle Ages (10th-12th centuries) among the warrior aristocracy was fundamentally centered on the paired practices of gift giving and violent taking, inextricably linked elements of the same basic symbolic economy. These performative practices cannot be understood without reference to a concept of the sacred, which anchored and governed the performances, providing the goal and rationale of social and military action. After focussing on anthropological theory, social history, and chronicles, the author turns to the "literary" persona of the hero as seen in the epic. He argues that the hero was specifically a narrative touchstone used for reflection on the nature and limits of aggressive identity formation among the medieval warrior elite; the hero can be seen, from a theoretical perspective, as a "supplement" to his own society, who both perfectly incarnated its values but also, in attaining full integrity, short-circuited the very mechanisms of identity formation and reciprocity which undergirded the society. The book shows that the relationship between warriors, heroes, and their opponents (especially Saracens) must be understood as a complex, tri-partite structure - not a simple binary opposition - in which the identity of each constituent depends on the other two. ANDREW COWELL isAssociate Professor of the Department of French and Italian, and the Department of Linguistics, at the University of Colorado.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAristocracy (Social class)xHistoryyTo 1500. 0aCeremonial exchangexHistoryyTo 1500. 0aHeroes in literature. 0aIdentity (Psychology). 0aLiterature, MedievalxHistory and criticism. 4aFrench Studies. 4aMedieval History. 4aMedieval Literature. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aGifts.  aHero.  aIdentity Formation.  aMedieval.  aMiddle Ages.  aPerformance.  aSacred.  aSaracens.  aSocial Action.  aViolence.  aWarrior Aristocracy.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781846155727?lo